<br>
My arguement is that if society has the right to deprive people of freedom for committing crimes (a fact I doubt ANYONE would dispute), then they have the right to deprive people of their lives if the crime warrants it.  It is both a deterrent and a punishment system.  (before you try and argue it doesn't deter, let me just point out that I can 100% guarentee that someone that is executed will not repeat their crime).<br>
<br>
Note that Del made an error - the defendant doesn't have to prove beyond a doubt his innocence - he just has to cast doubt on the proof of his guilt.  The burden of proof lies with the prosecution, ALWAYS. <p></br>

